# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: 1800-01-united-states-senate-elections
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:1800-01-united-states-senate-elections/1788-89-united-states-senate-elections] The **1788–1789 United States Senate elections** were the first U.S.
[src:1800-01-united-states-senate-elections/1788-89-united-states-senate-elections] Senate elections following the adoption of the Constitution of the United States.
[src:1800-01-united-states-senate-elections/1788-89-united-states-senate-elections] They coincided with the election of George Washington as the first president of the United States.
[src:1800-01-united-states-senate-elections/1788-89-united-states-senate-elections] As these elections were prior to the ratification of the Seventeenth Amendment in 1913, senators were chosen by state legislatures.
[src:1800-01-united-states-senate-elections/1788-89-united-states-senate-elections] Senators were elected over a wide range of time throughout 1788 and 1789.
[src:1800-01-united-states-senate-elections/1788-89-united-states-senate-elections] Pennsylvania was the first state to select its senators on September 30, 1788, and South Carolina was the last state on January 22, 1789.
[src:1800-01-united-states-senate-elections/1788-89-united-states-senate-elections] New York, North Carolina, and Rhode Island elected their senators between July 16, 1789, and June 12, 1790, after the convening of Congress.
[src:1800-01-united-states-senate-elections/1788-89-united-states-senate-elections] Among the original 13 states, ten of them selected their senators prior to the official start of the 1st United States Congress on March 4, 1789, ranging from Pennsylvania in September 1788 to South Carolina in January 1789.
[src:1800-01-united-states-senate-elections/1788-89-united-states-senate-elections] New York failed to elect its senators until July 1789.
[src:1800-01-united-states-senate-elections/1788-89-united-states-senate-elections] North Carolina and Rhode Island did not ratify the Constitution until after the 1st Congress began; North Carolina then elected its senators in November 1789, but Rhode Island failed to ratify the Constitution until 1790.
[src:1800-01-united-states-senate-elections/1788-89-united-states-senate-elections] Under Article I, Section 3, Clause 2 of the U.S.
[src:1800-01-united-states-senate-elections/1788-89-united-states-senate-elections] Constitution, the actual division of the Senate's seats into the three classes was not performed until after the 1st Congress convened.
[src:1800-01-united-states-senate-elections/1788-89-united-states-senate-elections] Thus, the 20 elected senators from the ten initial states did not know ahead of time whether they would serve Class 1's interim two-year term, Class 2's interim four-year term, or the full six-year term of Class 3.
[src:1800-01-united-states-senate-elections/1788-89-united-states-senate-elections] Then starting with New York, a random draw determined which classes each new state's seats would belong to while keeping the three classes as close to the same size as possible.
[src:1800-01-united-states-senate-elections/1788-89-united-states-senate-elections] Among the initial 20 senators elected before the 1st Congress began on March 4, 1789, 13 of them were Pro-Administration.
[src:1800-01-united-states-senate-elections/1788-89-united-states-senate-elections] New York failed to elect its senators until after the Congress began, so its seats are labelled here as "Vacant." North Carolina and Rhode Island did not ratify the Constitution until after the Congress began, so their seats are not included here.
[src:1800-01-united-states-senate-elections/1788-89-united-states-senate-elections] Article I, Section 3, Clause 2 of the U.S.
[src:1800-01-united-states-senate-elections/1788-89-united-states-senate-elections] The allocation of the classes by lot then took place in May 1789, two months after the first Congress began in March 1789.
[src:1800-01-united-states-senate-elections/1788-89-united-states-senate-elections] New York was then the first to be treated as a "new state admitted to the Union" under this process when they elected their senators in July 1789, drawing lots to determine which classes their seats would belong to while keeping the three classes as close to the same size as possible.
[src:1800-01-united-states-senate-elections/1788-89-united-states-senate-elections] In these general elections, the winners were elected in advance of March 4, 1789, the date set to be the beginning of the 1st Congress.
[src:1800-01-united-states-senate-elections/1788-89-united-states-senate-elections] Ordered by state, then by the class that they were eventually assigned in May 1789.
[src:1800-01-united-states-senate-elections/1788-89-united-states-senate-elections] In these general elections, the winners were elected in 1789 after March 4; ordered by election date.
[src:1800-01-united-states-senate-elections/1788-89-united-states-senate-elections] The Maryland General Assembly convened on December 10, 1788, in order to vote for the inaugural holders of Maryland's seats.
[src:1800-01-united-states-senate-elections/1788-89-united-states-senate-elections] There were two candidates for each seat, and all four were of the Federalist Party.
[src:1800-01-united-states-senate-elections/1788-89-united-states-senate-elections] An outright majority (50% plus one) was required for a candidate to win.
[src:1800-01-united-states-senate-elections/1788-89-united-states-senate-elections] Charles Carroll won election over Uriah Forrest by a margin of 3.70%, or 3 votes, for one of the seats.
[src:1800-01-united-states-senate-elections/1788-89-united-states-senate-elections] This election was decided on the third ballot, after the first did not produce a majority and the second had both candidates tie.
[src:1800-01-united-states-senate-elections/1788-89-united-states-senate-elections] John Henry won election over George Gale by a margin of 2.44%, or 2 votes, for the other seat.
[src:1800-01-united-states-senate-elections/1788-89-united-states-senate-elections] This election was decided on the second ballot, after both candidates tied with pluralities on the first.
[src:1800-01-united-states-senate-elections/1788-89-united-states-senate-elections] In May 1789, the lot draw performed by the 1st U.S.
[src:1800-01-united-states-senate-elections/1788-89-united-states-senate-elections] Senate assigned Carroll's seat to Class 1, whose term would expire March 3, 1791, and Henry's seat to Class 3, whose term would expire March 3, 1795.
[src:1800-01-united-states-senate-elections/1788-89-united-states-senate-elections] It was the first such election, and before the actual election the New York State Legislature had to establish rules for proceeding.
[src:1800-01-united-states-senate-elections/1788-89-united-states-senate-elections] They decided to ballot separately, and then pass a joint resolution once they had concurred in the election of two candidates.
[src:1800-01-united-states-senate-elections/1788-89-united-states-senate-elections] On July 15, Schuyler was nominated first, and members of each chamber attempted to substitute the names of other candidates, including Ezra L'Hommedieu and Rufus King.
[src:1800-01-united-states-senate-elections/1788-89-united-states-senate-elections] These motions failed, and Schuyler was elected by a vote of 37 to 19 in the Assembly, and 13 to 6 in the Senate.
[src:1800-01-united-states-senate-elections/1788-89-united-states-senate-elections] King's election came after individual legislators and the two chambers failed to agree on the election of James Duane, Ezra L'Hommedieu, or Lewis Morris.
[src:1800-01-united-states-senate-elections/1788-89-united-states-senate-elections] King was then elected unanimously by the Assembly, and by a vote of 11 to 8 in the Senate.
[src:1800-01-united-states-senate-elections/1788-89-united-states-senate-elections] On July 16, Schuyler and King were appointed to the U.S.
[src:1800-01-united-states-senate-elections/1788-89-united-states-senate-elections] Senate by a joint resolution of the State Legislature.
[src:1800-01-united-states-senate-elections/1788-89-united-states-senate-elections] King took his seat on July 25, and drew the lot for Class 3, his term expiring on March 3, 1795.
[src:1800-01-united-states-senate-elections/1788-89-united-states-senate-elections] Schuyler took his seat on July 27, and drew the lot for Class 1, his term expiring on March 3, 1791.
[src:1800-01-united-states-senate-elections/1788-89-united-states-senate-elections] The 1st United States Congress convened at New York City, as did the regular session of the New York State Legislature in January 1790.
[src:1800-01-united-states-senate-elections/1788-89-united-states-senate-elections] Schuyler retained his seat in the State Senate while serving concurrently in the U.S.
[src:1800-01-united-states-senate-elections/1788-89-united-states-senate-elections] Schuyler was also elected on January 15 a member of the State's Council of Appointments which consisted of the Governor of New York, and four State Senators elected annually by the State Assembly.
[src:1800-01-united-states-senate-elections/1788-89-united-states-senate-elections] On January 27, the New York State Legislature resolved that it was "incompatible with the U.S.
[src:1800-01-united-states-senate-elections/1788-89-united-states-senate-elections] Constitution for any person holding an office under the United States government at the same time to have a seat in the Legislature of this State", and that if a member of the State Legislature was elected or appointed to a federal office, the seat should be declared vacant upon acceptance.
[src:1800-01-united-states-senate-elections/1788-89-united-states-senate-elections] Senator Schuyler, Federal Judge James Duane and Congressmen John Hathorn and John Laurance vacated their seats in the State Senate.
[src:1800-01-united-states-senate-elections/1788-89-united-states-senate-elections] On April 3, John Cantine, a member of the Council of Appointments, raised the question if Schuyler, after vacating his State Senate seat, was still a member of the council.
[src:1800-01-united-states-senate-elections/1788-89-united-states-senate-elections] Philip Livingston, another member, held that once elected a member could not be expelled in any case.
[src:1800-01-united-states-senate-elections/1788-89-united-states-senate-elections] On April 5, Governor Clinton asked the State Assembly for a decision, but the latter refused to do so, arguing that it was a question of law, which could be pursued in the courts.
[src:1800-01-united-states-senate-elections/1788-89-united-states-senate-elections] Schuyler thus kept his seat in the Council of Appointments until the end of the term.
[src:1800-01-united-states-senate-elections/1788-89-united-states-senate-elections] North Carolina was the 12th state to ratify the new United States Constitution, doing so in November 1789, months after the First Congress had first convened.
[src:1800-01-united-states-senate-elections/1788-89-united-states-senate-elections] A few days after that ratification, on November 26, 1789, the two houses of the state legislature jointly elected incumbent Governor Samuel Johnston (who was considered pro-Administration) as North Carolina's first United States Senator.
[src:1800-01-united-states-senate-elections/1788-89-united-states-senate-elections] The minutes of the state Senate indicate that the two houses had actually voted for both U.S.
[src:1800-01-united-states-senate-elections/1788-89-united-states-senate-elections] Senate seats, but that no candidate received a majority for the second seat.
[src:1800-01-united-states-senate-elections/1788-89-united-states-senate-elections] Days later, the state Senate sent messages to the state House of Commons nominating candidates for the state's other Senate seat.
[src:1800-01-united-states-senate-elections/1788-89-united-states-senate-elections] These included William Lenoir, William Blount, Benjamin Hawkins, and Timothy Bloodworth.
[src:1800-01-united-states-senate-elections/1788-89-united-states-senate-elections] Hawkins (who was also pro-Administration at the time) was elected jointly by the two houses on December 8, 1789.
[src:1800-01-united-states-senate-elections/1788-89-united-states-senate-elections] The election was held on September 30, 1788.
[src:1800-01-united-states-senate-elections/1788-89-united-states-senate-elections] The Pennsylvania General Assembly, consisting of the House of Representatives and the Senate, elected Pennsylvania's first two United States senators, William Maclay and Robert Morris.
[src:1800-01-united-states-senate-elections/1788-89-united-states-senate-elections] Anti-Federalist William Maclay was elected to the two-year staggered term of the Class 1 seat, while Federalist and founding father Robert Morris was elected to the full six-year term of the Class 3 seat.
[src:1800-01-united-states-senate-elections/1790-91-united-states-senate-elections] The **1790–91 United States Senate elections** were held on various dates in various states.
[src:1800-01-united-states-senate-elections/1790-91-united-states-senate-elections] Senate elections occurred during the first midterm election cycle, which took place in the middle of President George Washington's first term.
[src:1800-01-united-states-senate-elections/1790-91-united-states-senate-elections] Senators were elected over a wide range of time throughout 1790 and 1791, and a seat may have been filled months late or remained vacant due to legislative deadlock.
[src:1800-01-united-states-senate-elections/1790-91-united-states-senate-elections] In these elections, terms were up for the nine senators in Class 1.
[src:1800-01-united-states-senate-elections/1790-91-united-states-senate-elections] After the June 25, 1790 elections in Rhode Island.
[src:1800-01-united-states-senate-elections/1790-91-united-states-senate-elections] Except if/when noted, the number following candidates is the whole number vote(s), not a percentage.
[src:1800-01-united-states-senate-elections/1790-91-united-states-senate-elections] In these elections, the winners were seated before March 4, 1791; ordered by election date.
[src:1800-01-united-states-senate-elections/1790-91-united-states-senate-elections] In these regular elections, the winners were seated March 4, 1791; ordered by state.
[src:1800-01-united-states-senate-elections/1790-91-united-states-senate-elections] All of these elections involved the Class 1 seats.
[src:1800-01-united-states-senate-elections/1790-91-united-states-senate-elections] In these elections, the winners were seated after March 4, 1791, the beginning of the next Congress.
[src:1800-01-united-states-senate-elections/1790-91-united-states-senate-elections] All of the senators from Connecticut were Pro-Administration through 1795.
[src:1800-01-united-states-senate-elections/1790-91-united-states-senate-elections] Oliver Ellsworth was re-elected in 1791.
[src:1800-01-united-states-senate-elections/1790-91-united-states-senate-elections] William Samuel Johnson resigned March 3, 1791, at the end of the 1st Congress and Roger Sherman was elected June 13, 1791, to finish the term.
[src:1800-01-united-states-senate-elections/1790-91-united-states-senate-elections] Charles Carroll won re-election over Uriah Forrest by a margin of 20.00%, or 15 votes, for the Class 1 seat.
[src:1800-01-united-states-senate-elections/1790-91-united-states-senate-elections] Senator, Tristam Dalton sought re-election but was eliminated before the third ballot.
[src:1800-01-united-states-senate-elections/1790-91-united-states-senate-elections] The third ballot saw the election of George Cabot, who had been a member of the Massachusetts Provincial Congress.
[src:1800-01-united-states-senate-elections/1790-91-united-states-senate-elections] The election in New York was held January 19, 1791, by the New York State Legislature.
[src:1800-01-united-states-senate-elections/1790-91-united-states-senate-elections] Incumbent Philip Schuyler's term would expire March 3, 1791.
[src:1800-01-united-states-senate-elections/1790-91-united-states-senate-elections] At the State election in April 1790, nominal Federalist majorities were elected to both houses of the 14th New York State Legislature, but many Federalists were friendly to the Democratic-Republican Governor George Clinton, party lines not being drawn very strictly then.
[src:1800-01-united-states-senate-elections/1790-91-united-states-senate-elections] The incumbent Philip Schuyler ran for re-election as the candidate of the Federalist Party.
[src:1800-01-united-states-senate-elections/1790-91-united-states-senate-elections] New York State Attorney General Aaron Burr was the candidate of the Democratic-Republican Party, but was at that time a rather moderate politician, opposing the ultras of both parties.
[src:1800-01-united-states-senate-elections/1790-91-united-states-senate-elections] Burr was the choice of both the State Senate and the State Assembly, and was declared elected.
[src:1800-01-united-states-senate-elections/1790-91-united-states-senate-elections] Schuyler was defeated despite the nominal majority of his party.
[src:1800-01-united-states-senate-elections/1790-91-united-states-senate-elections] Many of the Federalists took the opportunity to show their disapproval of both Schuyler's haughtiness and the financial policies of Alexander Hamilton, the U.S.
[src:1800-01-united-states-senate-elections/1790-91-united-states-senate-elections] Secretary of the Treasury and Schuyler's son-in-law.
[src:1800-01-united-states-senate-elections/1790-91-united-states-senate-elections] Besides, the Livingston faction of the Federalist Party felt betrayed after the election of Rufus King over their candidate James Duane in 1789, and now allied themselves with Clinton and later became Democratic-Republicans.
[src:1800-01-united-states-senate-elections/1790-91-united-states-senate-elections] Obs.: Burr had a majority of 5 votes in the Assembly, but the exact number of votes is unclear.
[src:1800-01-united-states-senate-elections/1790-91-united-states-senate-elections] In 1791, the legislature failed to elect due to a disagreement on procedure.
[src:1800-01-united-states-senate-elections/1790-91-united-states-senate-elections] The seat would remain vacant until 1793.
[src:1800-01-united-states-senate-elections/1790-91-united-states-senate-elections] Bradley and Moses Robinson were elected by the Vermont House of Representatives and Governor and Council in January 1791, anticipating Vermont's admission to the union.
[src:1800-01-united-states-senate-elections/1790-91-united-states-senate-elections] Vermont was admitted as the 14th state on March 4, 1791.
[src:1800-01-united-states-senate-elections/1790-91-united-states-senate-elections] The Senate had adjourned on March 3, at the completion of the 1st United States Congress; the 2nd United States Congress held a one-day session on March 4, and was not scheduled to convene again until October 24.
[src:1800-01-united-states-senate-elections/1790-91-united-states-senate-elections] As a result of this congressional schedule Bradley and Robinson had not been seated when the Vermont House of Representatives convened in early October, 1791.
[src:1800-01-united-states-senate-elections/1790-91-united-states-senate-elections] At this legislative session, some members suggested that the January election of Bradley and Robinson had been premature, since Vermont had not yet been admitted to the union.
[src:1800-01-united-states-senate-elections/1790-91-united-states-senate-elections] Bradley and Robinson volunteered to resign the credentials of their January elections; on October 17, the Governor and Council voted again, and selected Bradley and Robinson.
[src:1800-01-united-states-senate-elections/1790-91-united-states-senate-elections] The House of Representatives then voted a second time, and also selected Bradley and Robinson.
[src:1800-01-united-states-senate-elections/1790-91-united-states-senate-elections] Bradley was selected for the "short term" (Class 3), which expired on March 3, 1795.
[src:1800-01-united-states-senate-elections/1790-91-united-states-senate-elections] Robinson received the "long term" (Class 1), which expired on March 3, 1797.
[src:1800-01-united-states-senate-elections/1790-91-united-states-senate-elections] William Grayson died March 12, 1790, and John Walker was appointed to continue the term.
[src:1800-01-united-states-senate-elections/1790-91-united-states-senate-elections] Future President James Monroe was elected in November 1790 to finish the term.
[src:1800-01-united-states-senate-elections/1790-91-united-states-senate-elections] Monroe was re-elected in 1791 to the next term, as well.
[src:1800-01-united-states-senate-elections/1792-93-united-states-senate-elections] The **1792–93 United States Senate elections** were held on various dates in various states, coinciding with President George Washington's unanimous re-election.
[src:1800-01-united-states-senate-elections/1792-93-united-states-senate-elections] Senate elections were prior to the ratification of the Seventeenth Amendment in 1913, senators were chosen by state legislatures.
[src:1800-01-united-states-senate-elections/1792-93-united-states-senate-elections] Senators were elected over a wide range of time throughout 1792 and 1793, and a seat may have been filled months late or remained vacant due to legislative deadlock.
[src:1800-01-united-states-senate-elections/1792-93-united-states-senate-elections] In these elections, terms were up for the ten senators in Class 2.
[src:1800-01-united-states-senate-elections/1792-93-united-states-senate-elections] Formal organized political parties had yet to form in the United States, but two political factions were present: The coalition of Senators who supported George Washington's administration were known as the Pro-Administration Party, and the Senators against him as the Anti-Administration Party.
[src:1800-01-united-states-senate-elections/1792-93-united-states-senate-elections] Virginia's elections are considered a single race here.
[src:1800-01-united-states-senate-elections/1792-93-united-states-senate-elections] After the June 1792 admission of Kentucky.
[src:1800-01-united-states-senate-elections/1792-93-united-states-senate-elections] Two Pro-Administration senators (Benjamin Hawkins of North Carolina and John Langdon of New Hampshire) changed to Anti-Administration.
[src:1800-01-united-states-senate-elections/1792-93-united-states-senate-elections] The vacant seat in Pennsylvania was filled February 28, 1793 by an Anti-Administration senator.
[src:1800-01-united-states-senate-elections/1792-93-united-states-senate-elections] In these elections, the winner was seated before March 4, 1793; ordered by election date.
[src:1800-01-united-states-senate-elections/1792-93-united-states-senate-elections] In these regular elections, the winner was seated on March 4, 1793; ordered by state.
[src:1800-01-united-states-senate-elections/1792-93-united-states-senate-elections] All of the elections involved the Class 2 seats.
[src:1800-01-united-states-senate-elections/1792-93-united-states-senate-elections] In this special election, the winner was seated after March 4, 1793, the beginning of the next Congress.
[src:1800-01-united-states-senate-elections/1792-93-united-states-senate-elections] One-term Anti-Federalist William Few was defeated by fellow Anti-Federalist, James Jackson.
[src:1800-01-united-states-senate-elections/1792-93-united-states-senate-elections] Jackson won 24 votes in the Georgia House of Representatives and 11 in the State Senate for a combined total of 35.
[src:1800-01-united-states-senate-elections/1792-93-united-states-senate-elections] Few won 3 in the House and 2 in the Senate for a combined total of 5.
[src:1800-01-united-states-senate-elections/1792-93-united-states-senate-elections] Jackson took office as a member of the 3rd United States Congress on March 4, 1793.
[src:1800-01-united-states-senate-elections/1792-93-united-states-senate-elections] He would later resign in 1795 to run for his state's legislature.
[src:1800-01-united-states-senate-elections/1792-93-united-states-senate-elections] Incumbent John Brown, who had previously been elected in a special election was easily reelected with no opposition and 100% of votes from the legislators.
[src:1800-01-united-states-senate-elections/1792-93-united-states-senate-elections] Richard Potts won election to fill the seat vacated by Charles Carroll over Josh Hoskins Stone by a margin of 21.84%, or 19 votes, for the Class 1 seat.
[src:1800-01-united-states-senate-elections/1792-93-united-states-senate-elections] Senator Paine Wingate was not reelected.
[src:1800-01-united-states-senate-elections/1792-93-united-states-senate-elections] The New Hampshire General Court instead elected Federalist Samuel Livermore, a U.S.
[src:1800-01-united-states-senate-elections/1792-93-united-states-senate-elections] Livermore, like his fellow senator, John Langdon, would go on to serve as President Pro-Tempore during this term.
[src:1800-01-united-states-senate-elections/1792-93-united-states-senate-elections] Pro-Administration Samuel Johnston lost re-election to Anti-Administration Alexander Martin for the class 2 seat.
[src:1800-01-united-states-senate-elections/1792-93-united-states-senate-elections] The other senator, Benjamin Hawkins, switched his support from Pro- to Anti-Administration.
[src:1800-01-united-states-senate-elections/1792-93-united-states-senate-elections] There was a special election on February 28, 1793, for the Class 1 seat from Pennsylvania.
[src:1800-01-united-states-senate-elections/1792-93-united-states-senate-elections] Incumbent William Maclay's term had ended on March 3, 1791, but the legislature failed to elect a successor due to a disagreement on the procedure to be followed in the election.
[src:1800-01-united-states-senate-elections/1792-93-united-states-senate-elections] The seat remained vacant until Albert Gallatin was elected by the Pennsylvania General Assembly to the seat during this election.
[src:1800-01-united-states-senate-elections/1792-93-united-states-senate-elections] Upon agreement between the two houses of the Pennsylvania General Assembly, the House of Representatives and the Senate, regarding the procedure to elect a new Senator, an election was finally held on February 28, 1793.
[src:1800-01-united-states-senate-elections/1792-93-united-states-senate-elections] On February 28, 1794, the Senate determined that Gallatin did not satisfy the citizenship requirement for service and he was removed from office.
[src:1800-01-united-states-senate-elections/1792-93-united-states-senate-elections] Gallatin was replaced in the Senate by a special election in 1794.
[src:1800-01-united-states-senate-elections/1792-93-united-states-senate-elections] Anti-Administration senator Richard Henry Lee resigned October 8, 1792, just before the March 3, 1793 end of term.
[src:1800-01-united-states-senate-elections/1792-93-united-states-senate-elections] Anti-administration John Taylor of Caroline was elected October 18, 1792 to finish Lee's term and then re-elected in 1793 to the next term.
[src:1800-01-united-states-senate-elections/1794-united-states-senate-election-in-georgia] The **1794–95 United States Senate elections** were held on various dates in various states.
[src:1800-01-united-states-senate-elections/1794-united-states-senate-election-in-georgia] Senators were elected over a wide range of time throughout 1794 and 1795, and a seat may have been filled months late or remained vacant due to legislative deadlock.
[src:1800-01-united-states-senate-elections/1794-united-states-senate-election-in-georgia] In these elections, terms were up for the senators in Class 3.
[src:1800-01-united-states-senate-elections/1794-united-states-senate-election-in-georgia] This was the first election cycle with organized political parties in the United States, with the Federalist Party emerging from the Pro Administration coalition, and the Democratic-Republican Party emerging from the Anti-Administration coalition.
[src:1800-01-united-states-senate-elections/1794-united-states-senate-election-in-georgia] After the March 31, 1794 special election in Pennsylvania.
[src:1800-01-united-states-senate-elections/1794-united-states-senate-election-in-georgia] Seven senators who were considered "Anti-Administration" became Democratic-Republicans and eleven "Pro-Administration" became Federalists.
[src:1800-01-united-states-senate-elections/1794-united-states-senate-election-in-georgia] In these special elections, the winner was seated before March 4, 1795; ordered by election date.
[src:1800-01-united-states-senate-elections/1794-united-states-senate-election-in-georgia] In these regular elections, the winner was seated on March 4, 1795; ordered by state.
[src:1800-01-united-states-senate-elections/1794-united-states-senate-election-in-georgia] All of the elections involved the Class 3 seats.
[src:1800-01-united-states-senate-elections/1794-united-states-senate-election-in-georgia] There were no elections in 1795 after March 4.
[src:1800-01-united-states-senate-elections/1794-united-states-senate-election-in-georgia] The **Delaware special election** was held February 7, 1795.
[src:1800-01-united-states-senate-elections/1794-united-states-senate-election-in-georgia] Incumbent Senator George Read had resigned to take the position of Chief Justice of the Delaware Supreme Court.
[src:1800-01-united-states-senate-elections/1794-united-states-senate-election-in-georgia] Henry Latimer defeated the former Governor of Delaware, Governor of Pennsylvania and Continental Congressmen from Delaware and Pennsylvania by one vote.
[src:1800-01-united-states-senate-elections/1794-united-states-senate-election-in-georgia] John Henry won election over James Lloyd by an unknown number of votes for the Class 3 seat.
[src:1800-01-united-states-senate-elections/1794-united-states-senate-election-in-georgia] Incumbent Federalist Robert Morris, who was elected in 1788, was not a candidate for re-election to another term.
[src:1800-01-united-states-senate-elections/1794-united-states-senate-election-in-georgia] The Pennsylvania General Assembly convened on February 26, 1795, to elect a senator for the term beginning March 4, 1795.
[src:1800-01-united-states-senate-elections/1794-united-states-senate-election-in-georgia] Even though neither of Virginia's incumbent's terms were up, both resigned in 1794, leading to two special elections.
[src:1800-01-united-states-senate-elections/1794-united-states-senate-election-in-georgia] Future-president James Monroe resigned March 27, 1794 to become U.S.
[src:1800-01-united-states-senate-elections/1794-united-states-senate-election-in-georgia] Stevens Thomson Mason was elected November 18, 1794 and would become a Democratic-Republican in the next Congress.
[src:1800-01-united-states-senate-elections/1794-united-states-senate-election-in-georgia] Incumbent John Taylor of Caroline resigned May 11, 1794.
[src:1800-01-united-states-senate-elections/1794-united-states-senate-election-in-georgia] Henry Tazewell was elected November 18, 1794 and would become a Democratic-Republican in the next Congress.
[src:1800-01-united-states-senate-elections/1800-01-united-states-senate-elections] The **1800–01 United States Senate elections** were held on various dates in various states, coinciding with Thomas Jefferson being elected to the White House.
[src:1800-01-united-states-senate-elections/1800-01-united-states-senate-elections] Senators were elected over a wide range of time throughout 1800 and 1801, and a seat may have been filled months late or remained vacant due to legislative deadlock.
[src:1800-01-united-states-senate-elections/1800-01-united-states-senate-elections] Although the Federalists began the 7th Congress with a slim majority, Jefferson's Democratic-Republican Party took over the majority shortly thereafter due to mid-year special elections.
[src:1800-01-united-states-senate-elections/1800-01-united-states-senate-elections] By the time the first proper session of the 7th Congress met in December 1801, three seats had been gained by the Democratic-Republicans, leaving them with an overall majority of 17 seats and a government trifecta.
[src:1800-01-united-states-senate-elections/1800-01-united-states-senate-elections] After the November 6, 1800 special election in New York.
[src:1800-01-united-states-senate-elections/1800-01-united-states-senate-elections] In these special elections, the winner was seated before March 4, 1801; ordered by election date.
[src:1800-01-united-states-senate-elections/1800-01-united-states-senate-elections] In these regular elections, the winner was seated on March 4, 1801; ordered by state.
[src:1800-01-united-states-senate-elections/1800-01-united-states-senate-elections] In these special elections, the winner was seated after March 4, 1801; ordered by election date.
[src:1800-01-united-states-senate-elections/1800-01-united-states-senate-elections] Federalist Uriah Tracy was easily re-elected.
[src:1800-01-united-states-senate-elections/1800-01-united-states-senate-elections] William Hindman won election over Richard Tilghman Earle by a margin of 10.11%, or 9 votes, for the Class 3 seat.
[src:1800-01-united-states-senate-elections/1800-01-united-states-senate-elections] The Maryland legislature failed to elect a senator before the March 4, 1801 beginning of the term.
[src:1800-01-united-states-senate-elections/1800-01-united-states-senate-elections] As such, William Hindman was appointed to fill the vacancy, and retired when a successor was elected.
[src:1800-01-united-states-senate-elections/1800-01-united-states-senate-elections] Robert Wright won election over William Winder by a margin of 39.53%, or 34 votes, for the Class 3 seat.
